    "answer_id" : 17081541,
    "question_id" : 2442599,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>I am using NetBeans IDE 7.3 and this is how I go about centralizing my JFrame\nMake sure you click on the JFrame Panel and go to your JFrame property bar,click on the Code bar and select Generate Center check box.</p>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
      "user_type" : "does_not_exist",
      "display_name" : "user3025039"
    },
    "is_accepted" : false,
    "score" : 15,
    "last_activity_date" : 1424771063,
    "last_edit_date" : 1424771063,
    "creation_date" : 1418656838,
    "answer_id" : 27487288,
    "question_id" : 2442599,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 3.0",
    "body" : "<p>As simple as this...</p>\n\n<pre><code>setSize(220, 400);\nsetLocationRelativeTo(null);  \n</code></pre>\n\n<p>or if you are using a frame then set the frame to </p>\n\n<pre><code>frame.setSize(220, 400);\nframe.setLocationRelativeTo(null);  \n</code></pre>\n\n<p>For clarification, <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/awt/Window.html#setLocationRelativeTo(java.awt.Component)\">from the docs</a>:</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>If the component is null, or the GraphicsConfiguration associated with this component is null, the window is placed in the center of the screen.</p>\n</blockquote>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
